Date: Mon 12 Nov 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Agencia EFE (via Cccomtex), Mon 12 Nov 2001 [edited

Nicaragua: Concern about the High Rate of Dengue Fever
------------------------------------------------------
MANAGUA: Nicaraguan Health Ministry officials on Monday expressed their
concern about the high incidence of dengue fever this year that has already
resulted in 11 deaths. Juan Jose Amador, head of epidemiology at the
Nicaraguan Health Ministry, said 4 people have died due to dengue fever
since September alone, increasing dengue-related fatalities to 11 thus far
this year and exceeding the number of deaths the disease caused over the
same period last year. "If this activity continues, we will have a higher
mortality rate this year, because total deaths last year were 12," Amador
said, adding that confirmed cases of the more serious hemorrhagic dengue
fever have risen to 222, much higher than the 91 cases reported over the
first 11 months of last year. Some 1390 cases of dengue fever have been
reported in Nicaragua so far this year, up considerably from the 741 cases
reported during the same time period in 2000.
Amador explained that most cases of dengue fever are reported in the
autonomous Caribbean region of Masaya, located southeast of the capital,
the western province of Chinandega and Greater Managua. Health Minister
Maria Angeles Arguello has allocated an additional $55 000 for spraying and
clean-up efforts aimed at eradicating the _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito that
transmits the disease. Spokesmen from the Managua children's hospital said
they are treating 10 suspected cases of hemorrhagic dengue fever but lack
the proper medication needed to cure the disease.
--
[A similar AP report was forwarded to ProMED-mail by Pablo Nart. Since
there is no substantial difference, only one of the 2 reports is reproduced
here. - Mod.CP
