[3
Date: Wed 14 Nov 2001
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source: Beacon Journal, Mon 11 Nov 2001 [edited

Hawaii: Dengue Fever Warning for Visitors
-----------------------------------------
Visitors to the Hawaiian island of Maui will be getting an unusual type of
aloha greeting in the coming weeks: a warning about dengue fever on the
eastern portion of the island. The number of confirmed cases in Hawaii has
reached 74, with the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) in
Atlanta confirming the first case of the mosquito-borne illness on the "big
island" of Hawaii. So far 56 of the cases have been on Maui, where the
first locally transmitted cases of dengue appeared in early September. The
CDC said that it was the first outbreak of dengue in Hawaii in more than 56
years.
Officials said the chance of travelers contracting the mosquito-borne
illness is slim, but is not unheard of in places where the disease exists.
Symptoms of the rarely fatal viral disease include severe headache, fever
and rash. The CDC said there is no vaccine for preventing dengue, but
visitors to areas where it may occur should protect themselves from
mosquito bites by using repellents, wearing long-sleeved shirts and other
covering, and relying on screened windows to avoid contact.
Health officials plan to distribute warnings through car-rental agencies,
hotels and tour operators. Some roads in the affected area were closed
because of large mosquito populations, including roads leading to
Wainapanapa State Park near Hana, Kahanu Gardens, and Blue Pool waterfall.
Details can be found at the Hawaii Department of Health Web site at

and on the CDC site at
(click on "travelers' health").
